to believe anymore.

00:00:07.841 --> 00:00:10.010 align:middle line:84%
>> People are basically
going to keep

00:00:10.010 --> 00:00:12.379 align:middle line:84%
on help uncover what
really happened.

00:00:12.379 --> 00:00:14.781 align:middle line:84%
>> I felt like something
was watching me.

00:00:14.781 --> 00:00:16.716 align:middle line:84%
>> We weren't given
all the information.

00:00:16.716 --> 00:00:18.885 align:middle line:84%
We weren't told the
entire story.

00:00:18.885 --> 00:00:27.961 align:middle line:84%
>>George Noory: And
welcome to Beyond Belief.

00:00:28.595 --> 00:00:29.796 align:middle line:90%
I'm George Noory.

00:00:29.796 --> 00:00:32.432 align:middle line:84%
You know practically every
computer we have has an

00:00:32.432 --> 00:00:36.269 align:middle line:84%
antivirus system on
it called McAfee.

00:00:36.269 --> 00:00:40.006 align:middle line:84%
Well, the McAfee is sitting
right next to me John McAfee.

00:00:40.006 --> 00:00:41.341 align:middle line:90%
John, welcome to the program.

00:00:41.341 --> 00:00:42.342 align:middle line:90%
How are you?

00:00:42.342 --> 00:00:43.276 align:middle line:84%
>> George McAfee:
Thank you George.

00:00:43.276 --> 00:00:44.044 align:middle line:84%
I'm great to have
to be here sir.

00:00:44.044 --> 00:00:44.744 align:middle line:90%
>> Noory: Good to see you.

00:00:44.744 --> 00:00:45.779 align:middle line:90%
Good to see you indeed.

00:00:45.779 --> 00:00:47.747 align:middle line:84%
What an incredible
career you have had.

00:00:47.747 --> 00:00:50.050 align:middle line:84%
>> McAfee: Well, I have some ups
and downs and certainly a lot

00:00:50.050 --> 00:00:54.120 align:middle line:84%
of tangents and it's been a wild
ride for me and I've enjoyed it.

00:00:54.120 --> 00:00:56.389 align:middle line:84%
>> Noory: When you
started off were you

00:00:56.389 --> 00:00:57.724 align:middle line:90%
into computers as a kid?

00:00:57.724 --> 00:00:59.793 align:middle line:90%
Did they have computers--

00:00:59.793 --> 00:01:01.861 align:middle line:84%
>> McAfee: When I was a kid,
they didn't have computers.

00:01:01.861 --> 00:01:04.530 align:middle line:84%
Actually, one of the
first computers ever,

00:01:04.530 --> 00:01:07.333 align:middle line:90%
ever made was a computer made

00:01:07.333 --> 00:01:09.135 align:middle line:84%
by General Electric
called the GPAC.

00:01:09.135 --> 00:01:12.038 align:middle line:84%
And it was used for
process automation.

00:01:12.038 --> 00:01:15.275 align:middle line:84%
I was fortunate enough to get
a job with General Electric,

00:01:15.275 --> 00:01:17.143 align:middle line:84%
the first year that
they came out.

00:01:17.143 --> 00:01:18.945 align:middle line:84%
There was no software
engineering at that time.

00:01:18.945 --> 00:01:20.747 align:middle line:84%
There were no programs
in school--

00:01:20.747 --> 00:01:22.148 align:middle line:90%
>> Noory: Amazing.

00:01:22.148 --> 00:01:23.683 align:middle line:84%
>> McAfee: And General Electric
did their own education programs

00:01:23.683 --> 00:01:27.087 align:middle line:84%
so I went through a very
intensive software engineering

00:01:27.087 --> 00:01:30.357 align:middle line:84%
school at G.E. This is at--
while I was in grad school--

00:01:30.357 --> 00:01:31.491 align:middle line:90%
>> Noory: Learning as you went--

00:01:31.491 --> 00:01:32.492 align:middle line:84%
>> McAfee: Learning as I
went along and I've been

00:01:32.492 --> 00:01:33.860 align:middle line:90%
in computers ever since.

00:01:33.860 --> 00:01:35.628 align:middle line:90%
>> Noory: Now, at what point

00:01:35.628 --> 00:01:39.099 align:middle line:84%
in your career did you started
dabbling in the software

00:01:39.099 --> 00:01:41.668 align:middle line:90%
with the antivirus because--

00:01:41.668 --> 00:01:43.603 align:middle line:84%
I mean who would even
know there was a virus

00:01:43.603 --> 00:01:45.071 align:middle line:90%
to defend at that time?

00:01:45.071 --> 00:01:47.741 align:middle line:84%
>> McAfee: Well, I didn't
to be quite frankly.

00:01:47.741 --> 00:01:51.644 align:middle line:84%
A virus was discovered in 1986
called the Pakistani Brain.

00:01:51.644 --> 00:01:53.747 align:middle line:84%
It was the world's
first computer virus.

00:01:53.747 --> 00:01:55.148 align:middle line:90%
>> Noory: Developed?

00:01:55.148 --> 00:01:57.817 align:middle line:84%
>> McAfee: Developed by a two
brothers in Lahore, Pakistan.

00:01:57.817 --> 00:02:00.653 align:middle line:84%
For an odd place for such
technology to come from

00:02:00.653 --> 00:02:04.257 align:middle line:84%
but no one had conceived
to the concept of a program

00:02:04.257 --> 00:02:06.426 align:middle line:84%
that could replicate
itself and moved

00:02:06.426 --> 00:02:08.561 align:middle line:84%
and that's what a
electronic computer viruses.

00:02:08.561 --> 00:02:12.699 align:middle line:84%
It's a piece of software that
acts like a bacteria or a virus.

00:02:12.699 --> 00:02:14.634 align:middle line:84%
>> Noory: What do they
want to do with the virus?

00:02:14.634 --> 00:02:17.971 align:middle line:84%
I mean what-- each
virus has a plan, right?

00:02:17.971 --> 00:02:20.306 align:middle line:84%
>> McAfee: None of
them are good.

00:02:20.306 --> 00:02:25.512 align:middle line:84%
The Lahore brothers wrote into
the programs of a procedure

00:02:25.512 --> 00:02:27.514 align:middle line:84%
to wipe out everything
on the hard disk.

00:02:27.514 --> 00:02:28.314 align:middle line:90%
They thought it was fun.

00:02:28.314 --> 00:02:29.816 align:middle line:90%
And funny it was--

00:02:29.816 --> 00:02:31.284 align:middle line:90%
>> Noory: A little game.

00:02:31.284 --> 00:02:32.619 align:middle line:90%
>> McAfee: It was a game.

00:02:32.619 --> 00:02:33.920 align:middle line:84%
It was not funny to the people
who encountered the virus.

00:02:33.920 --> 00:02:36.589 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, when I first heard
of it which was about a day

00:02:36.589 --> 00:02:40.527 align:middle line:84%
after it was first discovered,
I called a friend, got a copy,

00:02:40.527 --> 00:02:43.496 align:middle line:84%
took a look at it and suddenly,
I saw how did they did it.

00:02:43.496 --> 00:02:46.700 align:middle line:84%
And I go wow, what an
incredibly beautiful technique

00:02:46.700 --> 00:02:47.967 align:middle line:90%
because it was.

00:02:47.967 --> 00:02:49.903 align:middle line:84%
In terms of software
engineering,

00:02:49.903 --> 00:02:51.905 align:middle line:90%
it was beautifully engineered.

00:02:51.905 --> 00:02:54.641 align:middle line:84%
No one had ever conceived
to the concept before.

00:02:54.641 --> 00:02:57.444 align:middle line:84%
And at the same time,
I saw how it was done.

00:02:57.444 --> 00:02:58.578 align:middle line:90%
I saw huh!

00:02:58.578 --> 00:03:00.814 align:middle line:84%
Well this is how you can
stop this or cure this.

00:03:00.814 --> 00:03:03.249 align:middle line:84%
And I wrote a little
program, put it out on--

00:03:03.249 --> 00:03:04.484 align:middle line:84%
we didn't have the
internet then,

00:03:04.484 --> 00:03:06.486 align:middle line:90%
we have bulletin board systems.

00:03:06.486 --> 00:03:07.587 align:middle line:90%
>> Noory: OK.

00:03:07.587 --> 00:03:08.721 align:middle line:84%
>> McAfee: And, you
know, within a month,

00:03:08.721 --> 00:03:10.356 align:middle line:84%
everyone in the world
had a computer program

00:03:10.356 --> 00:03:11.424 align:middle line:90%
and the rest is history.

00:03:11.424 --> 00:03:13.059 align:middle line:84%
>> Noory: And it was
fighting that virus.

00:03:13.059 --> 00:03:14.394 align:middle line:84%
>> McAfee: They got
rid of that virus, yes.

00:03:14.394 --> 00:03:15.361 align:middle line:90%
>> Noory: That is amazing.

00:03:15.361 --> 00:03:16.896 align:middle line:84%
And at what point,
did you decide

00:03:16.896 --> 00:03:18.898 align:middle line:90%
to form the company McAfee?

00:03:18.898 --> 00:03:20.733 align:middle line:84%
>> McAfee: Well, it was when
the next virus came out.

00:03:20.733 --> 00:03:23.069 align:middle line:84%
It was virus called
the Jerusalem.

00:03:23.069 --> 00:03:24.404 align:middle line:90%
>> Noory: They keep coming.

00:03:24.404 --> 00:03:25.472 align:middle line:84%
>> McAfee: They keep
coming and also

00:03:25.472 --> 00:03:27.073 align:middle line:90%
from the same part of the world.

00:03:27.073 --> 00:03:28.775 align:middle line:84%
But the second one was
the Jerusalem virus

00:03:28.775 --> 00:03:30.176 align:middle line:84%
and it was a very
odd little thing.

00:03:30.176 --> 00:03:32.078 align:middle line:90%
This is before we had Windows

00:03:32.078 --> 00:03:35.181 align:middle line:84%
and everything was
texted on the monitor.

00:03:35.181 --> 00:03:37.584 align:middle line:84%
It made all the letters
fall into a jumble

00:03:37.584 --> 00:03:39.319 align:middle line:90%
at the bottom of your screen.

00:03:39.319 --> 00:03:42.388 align:middle line:84%
Another very interesting
virus, so at that time,

00:03:42.388 --> 00:03:46.292 align:middle line:84%
everyone had downloaded
my program for the Brain.

00:03:46.292 --> 00:03:49.629 align:middle line:84%
It took about two days and
I wrote another program

00:03:49.629 --> 00:03:51.563 align:middle line:84%
for the Jerusalem
and at that point,

00:03:51.563 --> 00:03:53.666 align:middle line:84%
I knew that the world
needed this

00:03:53.666 --> 00:03:54.934 align:middle line:84%
because this is not
going to stop.

00:03:54.934 --> 00:03:56.302 align:middle line:84%
>> McAfee: You know
this is amazing.

00:03:56.302 --> 00:03:57.637 align:middle line:84%
>> Noory: Not going to stop
and it doesn't and it hasn't.

00:03:57.637 --> 00:04:00.406 align:middle line:84%
There are thousands and
thousands of viruses

00:04:00.406 --> 00:04:01.975 align:middle line:84%
that have been written
in the interim.

00:04:01.975 --> 00:04:05.979 align:middle line:84%
>> Noory: John, is it--
today is that a virus person

00:04:05.979 --> 00:04:09.182 align:middle line:84%
versus an antivirus
person every other day

00:04:09.182 --> 00:04:12.552 align:middle line:84%
because I noticed I'm getting
updates almost every other day

00:04:12.552 --> 00:04:13.153 align:middle line:90%
and stuff like that.

00:04:13.153 --> 00:04:13.720 align:middle line:90%
>> McAfee: Yes.

00:04:13.720 --> 00:04:14.854 align:middle line:90%
Yes, yes, it is.

00:04:14.854 --> 00:04:17.390 align:middle line:84%
In fact, there's almost
an unofficial war going

00:04:17.390 --> 00:04:19.491 align:middle line:84%
on between-- if you want
to call them the good guys

00:04:19.491 --> 00:04:20.493 align:middle line:90%
and the bad guys depending

00:04:20.493 --> 00:04:21.861 align:middle line:84%
on which sides you
happen to be on--

00:04:21.861 --> 00:04:22.862 align:middle line:90%
>> Noory: That's right, right.

00:04:22.862 --> 00:04:23.963 align:middle line:84%
McAfee: Right, but
keep in mind many

00:04:23.963 --> 00:04:25.932 align:middle line:84%
of the virus writers
have political agendas.

00:04:25.932 --> 00:04:27.133 align:middle line:90%
>> Noory: Uh-hmm.

00:04:27.133 --> 00:04:28.701 align:middle line:84%
>> McAfee: They-- They
feel that there are some--

00:04:28.701 --> 00:04:32.772 align:middle line:84%
some slight or some wrong
in some world government

00:04:32.772 --> 00:04:35.041 align:middle line:84%
that they're trying to
readdress, you know,

00:04:35.041 --> 00:04:38.211 align:middle line:84%
by bringing down the central
computer systems, what have you.

00:04:38.211 --> 00:04:41.014 align:middle line:84%
On the other side, we
look at them as vandals

00:04:41.014 --> 00:04:43.082 align:middle line:84%
because they are
destroying our work.

00:04:43.082 --> 00:04:46.052 align:middle line:90%
So there is a war going on.

00:04:46.052 --> 00:04:47.387 align:middle line:90%
>> Noory: To create a virus

00:04:47.387 --> 00:04:51.391 align:middle line:84%
to let's say shutdown the
power grid, that's being worked

00:04:51.391 --> 00:04:53.593 align:middle line:84%
on now I think by
rogue nations isn't it?

00:04:53.593 --> 00:04:54.127 align:middle line:90%
>> McAfee: Of course.

00:04:54.127 --> 00:04:55.228 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:04:55.228 --> 00:04:56.629 align:middle line:84%
>> Noory: And we're
probably doing it too.

00:04:56.629 --> 00:04:58.864 align:middle line:84%
>> McAfee: Well, if we aren't, I
would be very surprised George.

00:04:58.864 --> 00:05:02.468 align:middle line:84%
Of course and what happen
is the anti has been up.

00:05:02.468 --> 00:05:05.405 align:middle line:84%
If you think a couple of Lahore
hackers in Pakistan or Russia

00:05:05.405 --> 00:05:07.340 align:middle line:84%
or where have you,
they're going to do

00:05:07.340 --> 00:05:09.576 align:middle line:84%
so much damage even though
the damage they can do is

00:05:09.576 --> 00:05:10.977 align:middle line:90%
still great.

00:05:10.977 --> 00:05:14.514 align:middle line:84%
If you take a government with
all of its resources and money

00:05:14.514 --> 00:05:17.050 align:middle line:84%
and technical capabilities,
what would come

00:05:17.050 --> 00:05:19.185 align:middle line:84%
out will be horrible
beyond belief.

00:05:19.185 --> 00:05:20.553 align:middle line:84%
>> Noory: Do you
ever see the day

00:05:20.553 --> 00:05:24.757 align:middle line:84%
where another country would
shutdown, the satellite systems,

00:05:24.757 --> 00:05:29.362 align:middle line:84%
the computers and everything of
a country they're going after?

00:05:29.362 --> 00:05:30.763 align:middle line:90%
>> McAfee: Yes, absolutely.

00:05:30.763 --> 00:05:35.201 align:middle line:84%
And I think-- I think it would
be done by countries like China

00:05:35.201 --> 00:05:39.606 align:middle line:84%
or possibly Russia that that go
way beyond the technical aspect

00:05:39.606 --> 00:05:42.575 align:middle line:90%
of viruses and computer crime.

00:05:42.575 --> 00:05:45.712 align:middle line:84%
And they have merited with the
science of human engineering.

00:05:45.712 --> 00:05:48.948 align:middle line:84%
OK. And human engineering
is merely the science

00:05:48.948 --> 00:05:50.717 align:middle line:90%
of taking people and going--

00:05:50.717 --> 00:05:54.087 align:middle line:84%
this is how they're going to
behave in a certain condition.

00:05:54.087 --> 00:05:55.855 align:middle line:90%
You know, they'll watch you.

00:05:55.855 --> 00:05:57.323 align:middle line:90%
Let's say we want to put a virus

00:05:57.323 --> 00:05:59.759 align:middle line:84%
in George Noory's
computer, how do we do it?

00:05:59.759 --> 00:06:01.561 align:middle line:84%
Well, I would watch
you for a while--

00:06:01.561 --> 00:06:02.695 align:middle line:90%
>> Noory: Learn.

00:06:02.695 --> 00:06:04.330 align:middle line:84%
>> McAfee: I would see
what's your habits are,

00:06:04.330 --> 00:06:05.832 align:middle line:90%
what sort of foods you ate.

00:06:05.832 --> 00:06:07.033 align:middle line:90%
Are you a curious man?

00:06:07.033 --> 00:06:08.034 align:middle line:90%
Are you not a curios man?

00:06:08.034 --> 00:06:09.402 align:middle line:84%
If you're a curious
for example--

00:06:09.402 --> 00:06:10.103 align:middle line:84%
>> Noory: Do I go to the
ATM a lot?

00:06:10.103 --> 00:06:11.437 align:middle line:90%
>> McAfee: Right.

00:06:11.437 --> 00:06:13.473 align:middle line:84%
Well, if you're a curious man,
I would take a thumb drive

00:06:13.473 --> 00:06:16.109 align:middle line:84%
and drop it in front of your
car with a little label on it.

00:06:16.109 --> 00:06:18.144 align:middle line:84%
And let's say your favorite
thing is flying saucers

00:06:18.144 --> 00:06:21.247 align:middle line:84%
and I would say flying saucer
research, little label.

00:06:21.247 --> 00:06:22.982 align:middle line:84%
I guarantee you're going to
put that in your computer.

00:06:22.982 --> 00:06:24.183 align:middle line:90%
>> Noory: That's right.

00:06:24.183 --> 00:06:25.685 align:middle line:84%
>> McAfee: As soon as you
do, I own your computer.

00:06:25.685 --> 00:06:26.386 align:middle line:90%
>> Noory: It's got me.

00:06:26.386 --> 00:06:27.353 align:middle line:90%
>> McAfee: It's got you.

00:06:27.353 --> 00:06:29.822 align:middle line:84%
Now, this is a very
simple example.

00:06:29.822 --> 00:06:31.891 align:middle line:90%
You can imagine how more complex

00:06:31.891 --> 00:06:36.062 align:middle line:84%
and subtle examples would
be impossible to circumvent.

00:06:36.062 --> 00:06:37.730 align:middle line:84%
So this is how they're
getting in.

00:06:37.730 --> 00:06:42.535 align:middle line:84%
It's not by trying to solve
or unravel our encryptions,

00:06:42.535 --> 00:06:44.037 align:middle line:90%
or to bypass some firewall.

00:06:44.037 --> 00:06:46.739 align:middle line:84%
No. This is defined as
[inaudible] with access

00:06:46.739 --> 00:06:50.143 align:middle line:84%
to the system and
compromising her own computer.

00:06:50.143 --> 00:06:51.411 align:middle line:90%
This is how it happens.

00:06:51.411 --> 00:06:54.013 align:middle line:84%
>> Noory: I've got a personal
e-mail and I use Yahoo.

00:06:54.013 --> 00:06:55.415 align:middle line:90%
>> McAfee: Yes.

00:06:55.415 --> 00:07:00.520 align:middle line:84%
>> Noory: I noticed a couple of
days ago, I had an email from me

00:07:00.520 --> 00:07:02.455 align:middle line:90%
with some trashy stuff on it.

00:07:02.455 --> 00:07:03.589 align:middle line:90%
[ Laughter ]

00:07:03.589 --> 00:07:05.591 align:middle line:90%
>> Noory: I didn't send it.

00:07:05.591 --> 00:07:06.926 align:middle line:90%
>> McAfee: No of course--

00:07:06.926 --> 00:07:08.661 align:middle line:84%
>> Noory: -- but it clearly
had my email address on it.

00:07:08.661 --> 00:07:09.896 align:middle line:90%
>> McAfee: Absolutely.

00:07:09.896 --> 00:07:10.463 align:middle line:90%
>> Noory: What happened?

00:07:10.463 --> 00:07:11.264 align:middle line:90%
>> McAfee: OK.

00:07:11.264 --> 00:07:12.231 align:middle line:90%
This is a very common thing.

00:07:12.231 --> 00:07:13.733 align:middle line:90%
OK. Sometimes it's malicious,

00:07:13.733 --> 00:07:17.070 align:middle line:84%
sometimes there's a
business reason behind it.

00:07:17.070 --> 00:07:21.207 align:middle line:84%
What happened is you got unto a
website and downloaded a cookie

00:07:21.207 --> 00:07:24.077 align:middle line:84%
which transferred your
entire contact list

00:07:24.077 --> 00:07:26.045 align:middle line:90%
to someone or a hacker.

00:07:26.045 --> 00:07:26.979 align:middle line:90%
>> Noory: OK.

00:07:26.979 --> 00:07:28.247 align:middle line:84%
>> McAfee: That contact
list now,

00:07:28.247 --> 00:07:32.485 align:middle line:84%
now he knows your email
address and all of your contacts

00:07:32.485 --> 00:07:35.655 align:middle line:84%
and you are also in the
contact list as yourself,

00:07:35.655 --> 00:07:37.724 align:middle line:84%
then everybody is
going to get an email.

00:07:37.724 --> 00:07:39.959 align:middle line:84%
Now, maybe a little bit be an
email saying something like

00:07:39.959 --> 00:07:42.628 align:middle line:84%
"Gosh, I tried this new"
whatever, "this new diet

00:07:42.628 --> 00:07:43.663 align:middle line:90%
and I loss 30 pounds."

00:07:43.663 --> 00:07:44.497 align:middle line:84%
>> Noory: And they
think it's from me?

00:07:44.497 --> 00:07:45.665 align:middle line:90%
>> McAfee: Anything is from you.

00:07:45.665 --> 00:07:47.266 align:middle line:84%
And we trust you
so they go "Gosh,

00:07:47.266 --> 00:07:48.401 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to go out
and buy it now."

00:07:48.401 --> 00:07:50.002 align:middle line:84%
And there's a link at
the bottom of the page

00:07:50.002 --> 00:07:52.472 align:middle line:90%
to order it for 99.95.

00:07:52.472 --> 00:07:55.441 align:middle line:84%
